{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_emmental_ver01/data/sn83045293/00517012750/1920091701/0343.xml":{"full_text":"If there is anything that cannot bear\nfree thought let it crack.\u2014Wendell Phillips.\nVol. 9\u2014No. 241.\nFINDINGS\nBT\nVICTOR L. BERGER\nFrear, the Enemy of\n\u201cPork.\u201d\nWhen \u201cPork\u201d Is Spruce It\nIs Hard on the Memory.\nThe Difference Between\nPolitical Capital and Real\nMoney.\nImmense Immigration for\nIndustrial Centers.\n\u201cReserve Army\u201d of Industry\na Menace Next Winter.\n\u201cAnd it may be added inci\ndentally that the aforesaid\nRepresentative Cox was known\nas one of the best little pork\ngetters for his district, in the\nCongress of those times!\n\u201cOf that fact Representative\nFrear of Wisconsin, the pre\nmier fighter against pork,\ndoubtless will have a distinct\nrecollection.\u201d\n(The Milwaukee Sentinel.)\n\nMaybe! Well, Frear has a good\nmemory for \u201cpork/' Only his\nmemory seems to have left ihim\nentirely when he was asked atiout\nhis connection with a spruce com\npany that did an immense busi\nness with the government when\nwe were building those aero\nplanes. Mr. Frear figured on the\nletterheads as the vice-president\nof the company.\n\nIt not only makes a big differ\nence whose ox is gored, but also\nwhose pork-barrel is attacked.\n\nIf a Southern Democratic con\ngressman wants a $50,000 post\noffice for a .town of 1,500 in\nhabitants\u2014that is rotten \u201cpork\u201d\nand fine political capital.\nBut if a Northern Republican\ncongressman is the vice-president\nof a lumber company which does\na wonderful war business with\nthe government, that is different\nmeat altogether. It is \u201cpremier\nham,\u201d so to speak\u2014not political\ncapital, but real money.\n\nFor\u2014Bob La Follette may b%\nthe triie prophet\u2014sometimes. A\nfat war contract, however\u2014that\nis the true profit, all the time.\nLabor conditions in Milwaukee\nunderwent a marked change in\nAugust so far as common labor\nwas concerned, according to the\nmonthly report of the United\nStates department of labor. Or\nders from certain industries fell\noff, and while the department\nhad no reports of large numbers\nof men being laid off here, tran\nsients from other states reported\nthat it was difficult to get work.\nImmigration also is increasing\nby leaps and bounds, with indica\ntions that the pre-war record will\nbe equaled this year, according\nto Anthony Caminetti, commis\nsioner general of immigration.\n\nOne of the rapid problems\ngrowing out of the rapidly in\ncreasing immigration is the de\nsire of the new arrivals to seek\nthe industrial centers. Despite\nthe fact that the factories in the\nindustrial centers have as much\nunskilled labor as they need, 75\nper cent of the aliens stay in the\nindustrial centers. The newcom\ners had heard of the big wages\nbeing paid in the east in factories\nand mines and they do not look\nfor employment on farms in the\nwest.\n\nThis will have a tendency, of\ncourse, to reduce wages without\ncorresponding reduction in the\ncost of living.\nAnd it will add to the housing\nproblem in all the large cities\u2014\na problem which has already be\ncome acute in New York, Chi\ncago and Philadelphia\u2014while the\nfarming sections are still com\nplaining of the lack of needed\nlabor.\n\nTo equalize the demands of\nlabor \u2014and on labor \u2014is very dif\nficult under the capitalist system.\n\nOn the one hand, the employ\ners, and especially the big em\nployers, want a big \u201creserve\narmy\u201d of labor, in order to be\nable to expand activities when\never expansion seems to be war\nranted \u2014and also in order to keep\ndown wages by keeping up com\npetition among the wage work\ners.\nAnd on the other hand, this\n\u201creserve army\u201d of working men\nnot only adds to the -pressing\nevils of living conditions in the\nlarge cities, but that \u201carmy\u201d nat\nurally becomes a great menace\nFive N. Y. Socialists Re-Elected\nMILWAUKEEANS\nARE DIVIDED ON\nPOSSIBILITY OF\nGENERAL PANIC\nMajority Are Agreed That\nPeriod of Depression Is\non Way.\nCHAOS INEVITABLE-WEBER\nMilwaukee businessmen, labor\nleaders, charity officials and em\nployment authorities were divid\ned Friday in their opinion on a\nprobable business depression or\npanic in the near, future when in\nterviewed by The Leader.\nSome declared that a panic, even\na slight business depression, would\nbe impossible; others said that not a\npanic, but a business depression,\nwould make itself felt, while still\nothers came out flatfooted in their\nbelief that industrial chaos is in\nevitable.\nThis is what they had to say:\nWants Artificial Panic.\nFrank Weber, business agent of\nthe Federated Trades council and\ncandidate for the United States sen\nate: \"Big Business is breaking its\nneck trying to create an artificial\npanic. Under such a condition it\nbelieves organized labor will com\npete against itself and thus force\ndown wage standards. The real\npanic is inevitable. Already the\nfinancial buccaneers of Europe are\nagreed that there will be a general\nrepudiation of war debts by all na\ntions.\u201d\nHarry Lippart, superintendent of\nthe government employment offlee,\n3rd and Wells Sts.: \"Present em- 1\nployment conditions do not indicate\nan immediate panic. There may be\na slowing up later on In some in\ndustries, but I don\u2019t see a panic.\u201d\nF. J.' Zimmerman, head of the\nZimmermapn Clothing Co., 544 12th\nSt.; \"I don\u2019t think tfiere will be a\npanic. I believe that there will be\na gradual readjustment of condi\ntions.\u201d\nSees Depression Coming.\nAdam Gross, head of the Gross\nCoal Co., 437 Broadway: \u201cWhile i\nthere is no indication at present of\na panic, particularly in our line, I\ndon\u2019t doubt but what there will be\na slack in business, but I don\u2019t think\nthat it will be an old-fashioned\npanic.\u201d\nJ. Burkart, of the A. Grossen\nbach Commission Co., 317 Broad\nway: \u201cI don\u2019t feel a bit alarmed.\nThere is Nothing to be afraid of.\u201d\nH. B. Stanz, head of the Stanz\nWholesale Cheese Co., 312 Broad\nway: \u201cNo! No! Never! We have a\ngreat shortage in production now.\nIt cannot come under such condi\ntions. What workers ought to do Is\nwork 10 hours a day instead of 8 and\nltill one of those. We need produc\ntion.\u201d\nPaul J. Kalman Co., building ma\nterials: \"I do not think that theie.\nwill be a panic, but there might be\na general depression.\u201d\nConditions Are Present.\nPaul F. Berndt, secretary of the\nUnited Building and Loan Assn.,\n1216 Walnut St.: \u2018fit is impossible\nfor me to fotsee such a thing. I can\u2019t\npossibly see it that way. We are\nmaking more loans than ever be\nfore.\u201d\nDavid Rowe, head of the Milwau\nkee Commercial school, Wells and\n3rd Sts.: \u201cThere are many condi\ntions at present that might create\na panic. If we don\u2019t get away from\nour one-man government and keep\nour skirts clear of the European\nleague, we are likely to have it any\ntime.\u201d\nMrs. Katherine Van Wyck, gen\neral secretary of the Associated\nCharities, 85 Oneida St.: \u201cThere is\nno Indication of a panic in OUR\nwork. However, people can have a\npanic if they think of it enough.\nThat Is the psychology of things.\nDtPORTATION OF LETVIAN\nREPRESENTATIVE STAYED\nNEW YORK\u2014A telegram from\nthe department of labor at Washi g\nton to Immigration Commissioner\nWallis on Ellis Island Thursday\nstayed the deportation of Allred\nNagel and his wife, who have been\nheld at the immigration station\nsince Nagel came here a month ago\nas the accredited secretary of lega\ntion from the new republic of Letvia.\nIt is understood that this action was\ntaken because of the health of Mrs.\nNagel.\nHUERTA MAYBE GIVEN\nMEXICAN CABINET POST\nSAN ANTONIO, Tex. \u2014President\nAdolph De La Huerta, who will re\ntire from the presidency of Mexico\nwhen Gen. Alvaro Ohregon assumes\nthe administrative offlee in January,\nmay be given a cabinet position by\nObregon, according to reports here.\nHe was expected to be made minis\nter of foreign relations.\nwhenever out of employment for\nany length of time.\nThe future of our country is\nfraught with great dangers.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nIf\u2014\nHenry Bulder, for many\nj years alderman-at-large in\nMilwaukee, were driving west\non Martin St., in his automo\nbile at the same time the State\n!St. bridge swung open for\njboat passage and, if the clutch\njon Bulder\u2019s car failed to work,\nj precipitating the auto, himself\nand his wife into the river,\nbringing death to both of\n!them, would the alderman be\n[partly responsible for the\nI tragedy?\nj \"Bulder and his associates in\nthe comomn council would be to\nblame for this thing,\u201d said Frank\nWeber, business agent for the\n[Federated Trades council in an\n[interview Friday. \"If they would\nhave seen to it a long time ago\nI that safety guards were put up\nl when the bridges are opened in\nstead of leaving the gap exposed,\nthe chances are that Bulder\u2019s car\nwould not have plunged into the\nriver.\u201d\n\u201cIt is a pity that persons can\nnot understand the danger in\nthings until half a dozen lives are\nlost,\u201d declared Phillip Bierman,\nformer member of the Chicago\nSafety commission. \u201cThe Bulder\naccident would not be the first\nto happen at State St. bridge, j\nSeveral years ago an auto truck I\ntook the plunge at the point be- j\ncause there was not only no!\nsafety rail, but not even a light.\nOne man was drowi\\ed at the]\ntime.\u201d\nPROTEST POOR\nGAS BY USING\nSMS IN CITY\nSale of Coal and Oil Burners\nUnprecedented, Say\nDealers\nAs an aftermath of the reduction\nof heating units in gas supplied by\nthe Milwaukee Gas Light Co., local\nhousewives gradually are dropping\ngas and are preparing to resort to\nwood and coal-burning stoves and\noil heaters.\nThat this form of protest is\ngaining rapidly in Milwaukee, was\nannounced Friday by local stove\ndealers, who asserted that the heat\ning reduction and the subsequent\nrefusal to drop rates, authorized by\nthe state rail commission, was caus\ning an unprecedented demand for\nstoves of all descriptions.\nHundreds Buying Stoves.\n\"We are experiencing an unusual\nly heavy demand for ranges, heaters\nand oil burners of all descriptions,\u201d\nwas the word from the Phillip Gross\nHardware Co., 3rd St. \u201cHundreds\nof persons are buying them, probably\nwith the purpose of circumventing\nthe low quality gas at high rates.\u201d\n\u201cThe demand for oil burners is\nheavier than we have ever experi\nenced in our business history,\u201d said\nan official of the Regal Oil Gas\nBurner Co., 204 Grand Ave. \u201cWe\nhave sold several hundred of, these\nburners during the past week.\u201d\n\u201cThe stove business received an\nunprecedented impetus during the\npast month,\u201d said an official of the\nStove Dealers Supply Co., 310 Chest\nnut St.\nFar Above Normal.\n\u201cOur normal sales number about\n600 during the aummlr months.\nWe have sold that quota and still\nhousewives are demanding stoves by\nthe hundreds. We expect to sell\nmore stoves by far than ever before\nin our history.\u201d\nMany complaints are being made\nagainst the quality of gas being sup\nplied local consumers.\nHousewives assert that it takes\ntwice as long with the present qual\nity of the product to prepare meals.\nThey assert that the rail commission\nwould have improved conditions if\nit had authorized a rate increase in\nstead of keeping the rates at the\nsame level and ordering a reduction\nof heating units in the gas.\nWOMAN GRABS GUN FROM\nBURGLAR;ARRESTS HIM\nGARY, Ind.\u2014Mrs. Anna Martinos\ndiscovered a burglar rifling the cash\nregister in her confectionery store\nThursday. He leveled a gun at her\nhead and warned, \u201cKeep quiet or\nI\u2019ll blow your brains out.\u201d Mrs.\nMartinos grabbed the revolver and\nbacking him against the counter,\nheld him at the point of his own re\nvolver until the police arrived.\n$75,000 Largest\nIncome Tax; 70c\nSmallest Here j\nA check for $75,000 was the!\nlargest payment received in the\ntliird quarterly installment of'j\nfederal corporation and individual\nincome taxes, according to an-)\nnouncement Friday by Collector j\nBurt Williams.\nThe money was paid by a large I\nlocal company.\nThe smallest check was for 70\ncents, paid by an individual.\nChecking up of installments\nsince Wednesday has not revealed\na single delinquency, according to\nWilliams. j\nUp to Friday noon, approxi\nmately $18,000,000 had been paid\ninto the collector\u2019s office, Wil\nliams said.\n\u201cIPs AWED BY\\ INFLUENCE AND INBRIB ED BY GAIN\nINDUSTRIAL\nCONTROL IY BE\nREVOLUTIONIZED\nBY LAIN IN ITALY\nGiolitti Meets Labor and Em\nployers on Plan for Com\nmission to Draft Bill.\nFURTHER PARLEYS SLATED\nBY CAMILLO CIANFARRA.\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent.\nROME\u2014A revolutionary change\nin the operation of industries\nmay result from seizure by Ital\nian workmen of manufacturing\nplants, it was believed here Fri\nday.\nPremier Giolitti, holding con\nferences with labor leaders and\nmanufacturers, Friday an\nj Same Conditions\nAs in U S. Caused\nItalians 9 Revolt\nThat the mild revolution of the|\n[workers in Italy, where industries:\njare being taken over right andj\n[left by the laboring classes, isj\n[the direct! outgrowth of the!\n[same conditions which obtain]\nI here, was the assertion Friday of]\nJoseph M. Guiliani, president of|\nthe Italian Mutual Savings bank.\n\u201cSaid Guiliani:\n\u201cThere are profiteers and money\n\u2022mongers in Italy just as there are\nin this country. The revolution!\nin the mother country is the out-j\nI growth of the same conditions]\njthat are heading this country in|\n!the direction of an upheavel. Thej\n[moneyed class in Italy kept on\n[heaping abuse after abuse upon!\n[the workingman until he was!\njunable to stand it.\n\u201cThe result is that he is taking j\n[over the industries for his ownj\n[good. Of course, I do not be-j\n[lleve that it is right that the*\njworker does this without making!\n'some restitution to the owners,\n|but that seems to be the way of?\n[things. The revolution had to|\n[come sooner or latter.\n\u201cWhat we need most qf all in!\n'this world to avoid such condi-1\nItions is a greater justice and lessj\ni personal greed.\u201d\nnounced appointment of a com\nmission to prepare a bill for the\ncontrol of industries.\nMembers of the commission\nsaid it was inconceivable their\ntask would be merely to settle the\npresent crisis, precipitated by\nmetal workers who took the\nplants from their owners. Dep\nuty Turati said parliament would\nenact a law to give labor a part\nin the management of industries.\nEmployes Fight Plan.\nPremier Giolitti\u2019s attitude at the\nconference was if the manufactur\ners and workers were unable to come\nto an agreement the government\nTurn to Page Two, Column Three.\nMANY~WOULD ADOPT WAIF\nLEFT ON BOYD DOORSTEP\nCooing and kicking contentedly\nin its crib in the Milwaukee Infants\u2019\nhome, the tiny waif left on the\ndoorstep of Mrs. Frances Boyd, 495\nJuneau PI., still remains unclaimed\nby the mother who deserted it over\ntwo weeks ago. Although the\nmother has shown indifference, it\nis not so with the vest of Milwaukee\nand many families already have filed\ntheir names as willing to adopt the\nyoungster, according to hospital\nauthorities.\nTchitcherin Hits U. S.\nNote To Italy On Russ\nComplete Failure or Deliberate Misunderstanding of U. S. to\nUnderstand Soviet Aims Charged by Bolshevik\nMinister of Foreign Affairs.\nBY W. N. EWER.\nStaff Correspondent for The Federated\nPress and London Herald.\nLONDON (By Cable)\u2014Com\nplete failure or deliberate refusal\nof the United States government\nto grasp what the Russian soviet\nrepublic is driving at is held up\nto the light in a wipeless dispatch\nreceived here from George\nTchitcherin, soviet commissioner\nof foreign affairs, by Peace Com\nmissioner Leonid Krassin.\nThis message is an open reply\nto Secretary State Colby\u2019s\nnote to the Italian ambassador.\n\u201cSecretary Colby\u2019s note,\u201d says\nTchitcherin\u2019s dispatch, \u201ccontains\nan attack on Russia\u2019s policy and\npolitical system so unusual in\ndiplomacy that Russia cannot\nleave it unheeded. First, the\nAmerican government supports\nthe principle of territorial in\nFRIDAY EVENING, SEPT. 17, 1920.\nBrew Workers\nFlay Fight On\nSoviet Russia\nWill Not Withdraw From A. F.\nilof L. Fear Injury to\nCause.\nCOMMEND IRISH REPUBLIC\nBy unanimous vote, the con\nvention of the International\nUnion of United Brewery, Flour,\nCereal and Soft Drink Workers\nadopted a resolution Friday, ex\npressing sympathy with the\nstruggles and the constructive ef\nforts of the workers\u2019 republic of\nsoviet Russia in the face of the\ninternational enemies of the\nworking class and protested\nagainst all present or contem\nplated intervention.\nA resolution recommending with\ndrawal from the American Federa\ntion of Labor, as being too reaction\nary, and joining of an industrial or\nganization in keeping with the spirit\nof the times was rejected after brief\ndiscussion.\nWould Weaken. Cause.\nThe tenor was that withdrawal\nwould only weaken the cause of or\nganized labor in general and if any\nfighting was to be done it should be\ndone within the organization and\nthrough education of the American\nworking classes.\nAbolition of Sunday work where\nit is still in operation or demand for\ndouble time pay for all Sunday and\nlegal holiday work was indorsed by\nadoption of a change of article 4,\nI section 28, of the international con\nstitution.\nResolutions were voted forwarded\nto President Eamon De Valera, duly\nelected president of the Irish repub\nlic, expressing, loyal support in his\nstruggle to secure recognition qf the\nIrish republic by the government of\nthe\u2019 United States.\u201d The resolution\nalso commends \u201cthe heroism &nd\npatriotism of Lord Mayor Terence\nMacSwiney, Cork, who is at the\np*int of death as a result of a hun\nger strike entered into as a protest\nagainst the inhumane barbarity of\nBritish rule in Ireland.\u201d\n\u201cProhibition Breeds Crime.\u201d\nThe adoption of the various reso\nlutions was followed by addresses by\nJohn J. Manning, secretary, union\nlabor trades department, A. F. of\nL., Washington, D. C., and A. Mc-\nAndrew, president, International\nUnion of Tobacco Workers.\nManning was emphatic in his\nstatement that the executive coun\ncil of the American Federation of\nLabor, at no time has been hostile to\nthe brewery workers. He appealed\nto the delegates to forget obout any\nTurn to Page Two, Column One.\nNO CLUE FOUND AS YET\nIN ELLIOTT MURDER CASE\nSAULT STE MARIE. Mich.\u2014Ad\nditional information regarding the\nmurder of George Elliott, aged 45,\nprominent farmer residing near Soo,\nOntario, has been pouring into police\nheadquarters, but thus far no clue\nhas been found as to the where\nabouts of Dougal Moore, aged 30, a\nfarm hand, who is charged with the\nmurder, and the two girls, Maggie'\nDock, aged 15, and Pearl Mouer,\naged 16, who are believed to have\nescaped with him.\nCONVICTED IN PLOT TO\nSMUGGLE BOOZE TO U. S.\nMINNEAPOLIS Frank Ring\nstood convicted Friday, r\u00bbot only of\nparticipation In a plot to smuggle\nwhisky from Canada, but for offer\ning a bribe to a former deputy sher\niff to shield him. Ring was one of\na dozen implicated in the famous\nWinnipeg-Minneapolis.whisky smug\ngling conspiracy. He pleaded guilty\nand is now under sentence of one\nyear. His sentence for bribery was\nexpected Friday.\nviolability and indivisibility of\nCzarist Russia. Second, the\nUnited States considers friendly\nintercourse possible only if our\ngovernment is non-soviet.\nPOINTS OUT EXCEPTIONS.\n\u201cThe only exceptions it makes to\nthis doctrine of inviolability are Po\nland, Finland and Armenia. Mr.\nColby considers demands for inde\npendence by these nations legal, in\nasmuch as czarist Russia annexed\nthem by force. He seems to think\nthat other oppressed nationalities,\nwhich were not annexed by force,\nand who desire independence are\nmaking illegal demands.\n\u201cSo whether they form a com\nplete separation or a federation with\nsoviet Russia, Mr. Colby would not\nsanction such action by the Georg\nian, Azerbadjian, Lithuanian. Lat\nvian, nor Ukrainian peoples.\nDistinction Incomprehensible.\n\u201cThis distinction is incomprehen\nsible. and probably the result of in\nsufficient information. Mr. Colby's\nTurn to Page Five, Column Two.\nEXPLOSION Si\nBYLiONTTO\nHAVE BEEN DUE\nTO AN AGGIDENT\nFormer Employe of French\nHigh Commission Arrested\nin Canada as Suspect.\nSANITY IS QUESTIONED\nNEW YORK\u2014A statement that\nhe believed that the Wall St.\nbomb explosion Thursday which\nkilled 36 person and injured 300\nothers, was due to an accident to\na dray loaded with explosives,\nwas issued Friday by Thomas W.\nLamont of Morgan Co.\nDisregarding statements of de\npartment of justice officials that\nthe explosion Was the result of a\n\u201cplot,\u201d Lamont said:\nThere are no reasons that ws\ncan find that would lead to a pre\nmeditated bombing. I can see\nnothing to be gained by such an\nact. Circumtsances of the occur\nrence surely do not point to an at\ntempt to wreck the Morgan offices.\nIf anybody really plotted de\nstruction of our building, I believe\nthat we would have been sent the\nwarning that is usual in such in\nstances. And we have not been\nthreatened in any manner. I be\nlieve the explosion was due to\nnothing more than an unfortunate\naccident to a dray loaded with ex\nplosives which I am Informed had\narrived on the site of the Stock\nExchange building addition across\nthe street from our offices.\nHAMILTON, Ont. Edward P.\nFisher, formerly employe of the\nFrench high commission, suspected\nof knowledge of the cause of the ex\nplosion, was arrested in Hamilton,\nOnt., Friday, on a charge of insanity.\nThomas Delahunty, caretaker of\ntennis courts at 93rd St. and Am\nsterdam Ave., Friday charged that\nFisher had told him two weeks ago\nthat \u201cWall St. would be blown up or.\nthe 15th.\u201d\nFisher\u2019s arrest came as the result\nof information given the Toronto\npolice by his brother-in-law, Robert\nPope, New York. Fisher and Pope\narrived in Hamilton from Niagara\nFalls. Fisher is also alleged to have\nsent post cards from Toronto to\nfriends in New York, warning them\nof the explosion.\nWarning on Card.\nGeorge F. Ketchledge, employe of\nB. F. Schwartz Co., said he re\nceived a card from Fisher from\nToronto which read:\n\u201cGet out of Wall St. as soon as\nthe gong strikes at 8 o\u2019clock Wednes\nday, the 16th! Good luck.\u201d Fisher\nis also said to have issued a warn\ning to Lieut. Arnaud of the com\nmission.\nThe Hamilton lunacy commission,\nDoctors McGillivray and Rosen\nburgh, visited the prisoner in deten\ntion room and examined him.\nThe officers who took Fisher in\ncustody said his conversation was\npeculiar. Fisher, they said, de\nclared he was once a sparring part\nner of Jack Dempsey. Pope sup\nplied the police with the story of\nFisher\u2019s activities during the last\nthree weeks.\nPlot, Says Palmer.\nWASHINGTON \u2014Atty. Gen. Mitch\nel A. Palmer, superintending the fed\neral investigation of the explosion,\nFriday held to his original theory\nthat the blast was a \u201csecond May day\nplot.\u201d\nWilliam F. Flynn, chief of the\nsecret service, questioned scores of\neye witnesses to the explosion, de\nclaring he had positive information\n\u201cthat the explosion was caused by a\ntime bomb, and that the deliverer\nof the bomb wakon was seen four\nblocks from the scene at the time of\nthe disaster.\u201d\nArrests of radicals is expected to\nfollow the activity of the federal\nauthorities. It was reported that\nWilliam D. Haywood, I. W. W.\nleader, is in New York and that his\narrest had been ordered as \"a pre\ncautionary measure.\u201d\nWE ALWAYS HAVE\nBACKED CONSTITUTION,\nHOAN WRITES D. A. R.\nMayor Daniel W. Hoan will he on\nthe platform Saturday night, in the\nAuditorium, when Milwaukee cele\nbrates Constitution day, under au\nspices of the Daughters of the Amer\nican Revolution.\n\u201cI accept with pleasure,\u201d wrote\nHoan to the invitation to act as one\nof the reception committee. \u201cThe\nSocialist party has always upheld\nthe constitution and I have always\nupheld it.\u201d\nHenry R. Rathbone will be the\nspeaker of the day.\nMADISONPOLICEMAN\u2019S\nTRIAL IN JEFFERSON\nMADISON \u2014By direction of Judge\nA. C. Hoppmann, of the Superior\ncourt. Matthew Lynaugh, Madison\npoliceman, who shot and killed Carl\nJandorf. a university student, last\nJune, will be tried in Jefferson.\nINDEPENDENCE DAY IS\nOBSERVED IN MEXICO\nMEXICO CITY \u2014Mexican inde\npendence day was celebrated Thurs\nday with elaborate ceremonies and\ngreat military display*\nOUSTED ASSEMBLYMEN\nELECTED BY BIG VOTE\nDESPITE FUSION TICKET\nCampaign Regarded Throughout State as Fight for Vindi\ncation of Principle of Representative Government \u2014Unions\nand Farmer-Labor Party Backed Legislators.\nHEAVY SOCIALIST VOTE EXPECTED IN NOVEMBER\nALBANY, N. Y.\u2014With receipt of word here that the five ex\npelled Socialist assemblymen had been re-elected in Thursday's\nspecial election in New York, it was reported that the right of the\nmen to seats will be challenged as soon as the house convenes in\nspecial session Monday night.\nDoubt was being expressed Friday whether sufficient strength\ncould be mustered to eject the Socialists a second time. Several\nmembers who voted for expulsion last winter have changed their\nview.\n\nNEW YORK\u2014The five Socialist expelled from the\nYork legislature at the last session on charges of disloyalty pre\nferred by Speaker Sweet, were returned with huge majorities in\nThursday\u2019s special election, complete returns Friday showed.\nThey are: Charles Soloman, 23rd district, Kings county; Louis\nWaldman, 3th district; August Claessens, 17th district, New York\ncounty; Samuel Orr, 4th district, and A. Dewit, 3rd district, Bronx\ncounty.\nCHUTES\nI. T. SHUTS\nlit KENT\nState Party Sees Election as\nStraw in Political\nWind.\nTo the New York Socialists:\nWisconsin sends its cheers in\ncelebration of your victory.\nEMIL SEIDEL,\nState Secretary, Socialist Party.\nThis was the message sent Friday\nby Emil Seidel, state secretary of the\nSocialist party of Wisconsin, to the\nfive Socialist assemblymen of New\nYork, who, after being unseated by\nfellow-legislators last fall, on\ncharges of \u201cdisloyalty and attempt\ning to overthrow the government by\nforce,\u201d were re-elected in special\nelections Thursday.\nSeidel\u2019s message was sent in care\nof The New York Call, the Socialist\norgan.\nHow He Reads News.\n\u201cWhen I looked at the morning\nSentinel to see what had happened\nin New York and failed to find any\nthing, I was convinced that the So\ncialists had won, for if they had been\ndowned it would have been printed\nall over the front page,\u201d said Her\nman Tucker of the Machinists, \"but\nwhen I was coming to the office on\nthe car I found the little news item\non the 10th page that I had previ\nously overlooked and found that true\nenough there had been a fine vic\ntory.\u201d\n\u201cThe re-election of the five So\ncialists ousted by the New York\nlegislature establishes the fact that\nthe people are awakening and de\ntermined to maintain their consti\ntutional rights, that they, and not\nan elective body, shall decide who\nshall represent them in a law making\nassembly,\u201d said Frank J. Weber, So\ncialist candidate for United States\nsenator.\nShows People\u2019s Minds.\n\u201cThe election in New York is a\nvindication of representative gov\nernment, and it is also a slam at the\niNew York assembly and especially\nto Speaker Sweet and his clique who\nengineered the ousting of the five\nrepresentatives of the electors. It\nshows also what is in peoole\u2019s minds\nthis year, and is an augury for the\ncoming election in Wisconsin,\u201d said\nState Senator Louis A. Arnold.\n\u201cThe re-election of the five So\ncialists in New York is proof that\nthe people still believe in represen\ntative government and insist upon it.\nThe election is a warning to congress\nand other representative bodies that\nthe expelling of representatives of\nthe peole will not be tolerated, ./is\nconsin will also re-elect Victor L.\nBerger in the same spirit of insist\nance on fundamental rights,\u201d was\nthe comment of Frank Metcalfe, of\nthe trades union Liberty league.\nNONPARTiSAIif LEAGUERS\nLEADING IN COLORADO\nDENVER, Col. \u2014Indications early\nFriday were the Nonpartisan league\ndealt a severe blow to the regular\nDemocrats in Colorado in Tuesday\u2019s\nstate primary election. Judge Tully\nScott was the only regular Democrat\nleading. His vote exceeds that of\nCallicotte, Nonpartisan league candi\ndate for the Democratic nomination\nfor United States senator, by 2,180.\nThe Nonpartisan gubernatorial can\ndidate had a lead of 4,080 over Rob\nert Higgins, Democrat.\nS3SISSKB\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Fair y*ri<l&s\nnight and Saturday. Warmer tonight.\nModerate westerly winds.\nWisconsin: Fair tonight and Saturday;\nwarmer tonight in eaat and south portions.\nTemperatures: 1 a. m.. SO; 2, 59; 3. 58;\n4, 58; o, 57; 6, 56; 7, SS: 8. 66; 9. 71; 10.\n73: It, 76; noon, 75; 1 P- m., T 8; 2, 79.\nTemperature 24 hours to midnight: Max\nimum 74; minimum. 59; mean. 66; nor\nmal 61. Midnight to 10 a. m.: Minimum.\n59; relative humkli'.y. 72; wind velocity at\n7 a. m., miles; direction of wind at 7\na. m,, west; sunrise today, 5;34; sunset,\n5:53.\nHOME\nEDITION\nPRICE THREE CENTS,\nThe campaign was regarded as\na fight for the vindication of rep\nresentative government. The\nFarmer-Labor party of New York\npledged its support to the five\nSocialists.\nDudley Field Malone, Farmer-\nLabor candidate for governor, is\nsued a statement saying:\n\u201cThe issue before the voters is:\nShall we have representative gov\nernment in New York state or the\nMAJORITIES GIVEN TO\nSOCIALIST CANDIDATES\nReturns received over long\ndistance telephone by The Mil\nwaukee Jewish Daily Forward\ngive the following majorities to\nthe Socialist assemblymen:\nOrr 1,200\nDewitt. 1,300\nCla6ssens 1,700\nWaldman 800\nSolomon 2,000\nprogram of anarchy advocated by\nLusk, Sweet and other reaction\naries?\u201d\nThe candidates were also support\ned by many of the labor organisa\ntions of the city, notably the great\nneedle unions. Members of the\nUnited Hebrew Trades were urged\nby their organization to stop work\nearly in order to vote.\nFollowing a study of the returns,\nSocialist officials announced that\nthey expected a heavy increase in\nthe party vote this fall.\nThe move to oust the Socialist*\ncame without warning on the first\nday of the session. After all mem\nbers had taken the oath, Speaker\nSweet suddenly called the five So\ncialists before him and bitterly ar\nraigned them, charging them with\nvarious offenses and declaring their\npresence in the assembly waa\n\u201cinimitable to the best interests of\nthe state and nation.\u201d\nHill quit Directed Defense.\nMajority Leader Adler then of\nfered a resolution suspending them\nuntil their case could be heard. It\nwas passed with but two dissenting\nvotes. Charles Evans Hughes and\nfour associates of the New York\nCity Bar Assn, sought permission to\nTurn to Page Two, Column Two.\nCHICAGOAN ELECTED\nAS NATIONAL HEAD OF\nSTATIONARY ENGINEERS\nThe National Assn, of Stationary\nEngineers concluded the final busi\nness session of its annual convention\nin the Auditorium Friday with the\nelection of officers and Indorsement\nof Rochester, N. Y.. as the next con\nvention city. The following are the\nnew officers:\nPresident, Alfred Johnson, Chi\ncago; vice-president, Richard Perry,\nChicago; secretary, F. W. Raven,\nChicago; treasurer, S. B. Forse,\nPittsburgh; trustee, Harry Hilton,\nLos Angeles; conductor, J. Albert\nJohnson, St. Paul; doorkeeper,\nFrank L. Guth, Cambridge, Mass.\nThe convention will come to a\nclose with the public installation of\nofficers and the annual ball in the\nAuditorium Friday night.\nENGLISH ENGINEERS UNION\nPLACE BAN ON OVERTIME\nMANCHESTER, England An\nembargo on overtime work on\nmaintenance jobs is being em\nployed as a weapon by the Lanca\nshire members of the Amalgamated\nEngineering union, who are de\nmanding a raise in wages. The em\nbargo involves the stoppage of ma\nchinery in ordinary working time to\ndo repairs and overhauling which\nwould otherwise be done when the\nworks were closed.\nEGGS AT 42 CENTS TO\nBE SOLD ON CITY MARTS\nEggs will be sold at 42 cents a\ndozen Saturday In four municipal\nmarkets, according to announcement\nFriday by City Sealer W. F. Steinel.\nThe markets are at 373 National\nAve., North and Farwell Aves.. Had\nley and 14th Sts., and Fond du L M\nAve. and 19Ui St,","height":"27798","width":"22083"}}
